FADE IN:

INT. DETECTIVE'S APARTMENT - NIGHT

MAYA, 30s, a weathered homicide detective with tired eyes and a sharp mind. Beside her, VIKTOR, a Russian crime boss with a scar across his left cheek and a tailored suit. On the desk: a revolver, a phone, a laptop. Maya wears a coat and scarf. fog drifts across the lot.

A crowd of pedestrians moves past.

The room is dim. Shadows pool in the corners. A black sedan idles outside, headlights cutting across the wet pavement.

MAYA

Where were you on the night of the fourteenth?

VIKTOR

(whispering)
I don't have time for this. We need to move.

MAYA

The package is in the warehouse. Top shelf.

VIKTOR

He's lying. I can see it in his eyes.

Her hand hovers over the gun on the table. smoke curls from the ashtray.

MAYA (CONT'D)

He's lying. I can see it in his eyes.

VIKTOR

Where were you on the night of the fourteenth?

MAYA

Tell me everything you remember.

VIKTOR

(into phone)
It was you. The whole time, it was you.

MAYA

There's a leak somewhere in the precinct.

The morgue is cold. Steel tables. A clipboard hangs from a hook. A revolver and a cellphone sit sealed in an evidence bag.

Smoke curls from a forgotten cigarette in the ashtray. A briefcase sits open on the floor, papers spilling out.

EXT. WAREHOUSE DISTRICT - DAY

Viktor steps into frame. On the desk: a pistol, a knife, a wallet, a badge. Viktor wears a suit and tie. smoke curls from the ashtray.

Sirens wail in the distance. A helicopter circles overhead. The pistol sits on the table between them, untouched.

VIKTOR

Get down! Now!

VIKTOR

She knew it would come to this.

VIKTOR

I have to go. There's something I need to check.

VIKTOR

It was you. The whole time, it was you.

VIKTOR

Don't follow me. Please.

He pours another bourbon and stares out the window. thunder rolls in the distance.

VIKTOR (CONT'D)

I'll handle it from here.

VIKTOR

I had no choice.

VIKTOR

I'm telling you, the evidence is gone.

VIKTOR

He's lying. I can see it in his eyes.

VIKTOR

She knew it would come to this.

VIKTOR

The evidence doesn't lie. Even if you do.

Bookshelves line the wall: legal volumes, photographs, a model ship behind glass. A whiskey decanter sits half-empty.

Glass crunches underfoot. Debris from last night's break-in still litters the entryway. Lightning flickers through the blinds.

INT. WAREHOUSE - DAWN

RAY, 60s, Maya's grizzled partner, three months from retirement. Beside him, DR. CHEN, a meticulous forensic pathologist with steel-rimmed glasses. On the desk: a photograph, a lighter, a cigarette, a bottle, a glass. Ray wears a jacket and boots. thunder rolls in the distance.

Files cover the desk: photographs, transcripts, a coffee-stained notebook. A revolver gleams under the lamp.

RAY

I'll handle it from here.

DR. CHEN

There's a leak somewhere in the precinct.

RAY

Drop the gun and step away from the desk.

DR. CHEN

We need to talk. Privately.

RAY

I made a promise. I intend to keep it.

DR. CHEN

There's blood on your shirt.

She lights a cigarette and the flame trembles. rain hammers the windows.

RAY (CONT'D)

You promised me this was over.

DR. CHEN

Drop the gun and step away from the desk.

RAY

Pull the file on the Henderson case. All of it.

DR. CHEN

Walk away. I won't ask twice.

RAY

I don't have time for this. We need to move.

DR. CHEN

I've seen this pattern before. Three years ago.

RAY

Don't follow me. Please.

The bridge stretches into fog. A boat horn echoes from the river. A figure stands at the railing, coat whipping in the wind.

The motorcycle's engine ticks as it cools. A leather jacket lies draped across the seat. Keys glint on the floor.

EXT. ROOFTOP - DUSK

Dr. Chen steps into frame. On the desk: a camera, a flashlight, a rope. Dr. Chen wears a dress and gloves. rain hammers the windows.

Reporters press against the cordon.

Steam rises from a mug of coffee. The laptop's fan whines. Somewhere down the hall, a phone rings and rings.

DR. CHEN

Pull the file on the Henderson case. All of it.

DR. CHEN

It's not what you think.

DR. CHEN

I had no choice.

DR. CHEN

Look at me. Hey — look at me.

His phone vibrates. He doesn't pick up. an explosion rocks the building.

DR. CHEN (CONT'D)

I've seen this pattern before. Three years ago.

DR. CHEN

I have to go. There's something I need to check.

DR. CHEN

I'll handle it from here.

DR. CHEN

There's blood on your shirt.

DR. CHEN

Look at me. Hey — look at me.

DR. CHEN

Don't come any closer.

DR. CHEN

You don't understand what they're capable of.

DR. CHEN

I have to go. There's something I need to check.

The room is dim. Shadows pool in the corners. A black sedan idles outside, headlights cutting across the wet pavement.

The door opens. MARCUS, 40s, the precinct captain, eyes hidden behind aviators.

MARCUS

The package is in the warehouse. Top shelf.

DR. CHEN

It was you. The whole time, it was you.

Reporters press against the cordon. Camera flashes strobe across the wet street. A microphone is thrust toward her face.

INT. POLICE STATION - CONTINUOUS

JANE, 20s, an investigative journalist with a notebook full of dangerous questions. Marcus watches from the corner. On the desk: a cigar, a envelope, a letter, a ring. Jane wears a uniform and cap. an explosion rocks the building.

Outside, rain hammers the alley. A stray dog barks from the shadows. Fog drifts across the asphalt.

JANE

I'm telling you, the evidence is gone.

MARCUS

(with a smirk)
Don't come any closer.

JANE

Where were you on the night of the fourteenth?

MARCUS

I don't have time for this. We need to move.

JANE

The package is in the warehouse. Top shelf.

The badge on his belt catches the light. blood pools on the tile.

JANE (CONT'D)

We need to talk. Privately.

MARCUS

The package is in the warehouse. Top shelf.

JANE

Get down! Now!

MARCUS

We were partners. That has to mean something.

JANE

We need to talk. Privately.

Sirens wail in the distance. A helicopter circles overhead. The pistol sits on the table between them, untouched.

Two patrol cars block the alley. An ambulance idles, lights cycling. The crowd of onlookers grows by the minute.

INT. INTERROGATION ROOM - MOMENTS LATER

Marcus steps into frame. On the desk: a folder, a notebook, a newspaper, a umbrella, a bag. Marcus wears a hoodie and jeans. blood pools on the tile.

The crowd parts. Two guards in black tactical gear sweep the perimeter, rifles low. A drone hovers above.

MARCUS

Tell me everything you remember.

MARCUS

I've seen this pattern before. Three years ago.

MARCUS

Get down! Now!

MARCUS

She knew it would come to this.

MARCUS

I have to go. There's something I need to check.

MARCUS

It was you. The whole time, it was you.

She tightens her scarf and steps into the rain. lightning flickers outside.

MARCUS (CONT'D)

I'm telling you, the evidence is gone.

MARCUS

You promised me this was over.

MARCUS

Where were you on the night of the fourteenth?

MARCUS

(shouting)
Tell me everything you remember.

MARCUS

It was you. The whole time, it was you.

MARCUS

There's a leak somewhere in the precinct.

Files cover the desk: photographs, transcripts, a coffee-stained notebook. A revolver gleams under the lamp.

A truck rumbles past. Pigeons scatter. The taxi driver leans on his horn and shouts something obscene out the window.

